root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>13822</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-0026</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-0026.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Non-negatively generated basis yields positive generation</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="tomdejong.xml"
type="local"
addr="tomdejong">Tom de Jong</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="martinescardo.xml"
type="local"
addr="martinescardo">Martín Hötzel Escardó</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> be a <fr:link
href="jms-001S.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-001S">pointed</fr:link> continuous dcpo presented by a basis <fr:tex>B \subseteq  A</fr:tex> such that each element of <fr:tex>B</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-002J.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-002J">non-negatively generated</fr:link> in <fr:tex>A</fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex>A</fr:tex> is <fr:link
href="jms-0023.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-0023">positively generated</fr:link>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>13818</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:addr>#512</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-512.xml</fr:route><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="tomdejong.xml"
type="local"
addr="tomdejong">Tom de Jong</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="martinescardo.xml"
type="local"
addr="martinescardo">Martín Hötzel Escardó</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-0026</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>We must show that for any <fr:tex>a \in  A</fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex>a  \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup _{p: \mathsf { pos } \, a}a</fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex>B_a</fr:tex> be the subset <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left \{ b  \in  B  \mid  b \ll  a \right \} \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>. By assumption, it suffices to check that <fr:tex>\bigsqcup  B_a  \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup _{p: \mathsf { pos } \, a}a</fr:tex>. Fixing <fr:tex>b \in  B_a</fr:tex>, we must check that <fr:tex>b \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup _{p: \mathsf { pos } \, a}a</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>As <fr:tex>b</fr:tex> is assumed to be <fr:link
href="jms-002J.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-002J">non-negatively generated</fr:link>, we have <fr:tex>b= \bigsqcup _{p: \lnot { \mathopen {} \left ( b= \bot \right ) \mathclose {}} }b</fr:tex> so to check <fr:tex>b \sqsubseteq \bigsqcup _{p: \mathsf { pos } \, a}a</fr:tex> it suffices to check that <fr:tex>\lnot { \mathopen {} \left ( b= \bot \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> implies that <fr:tex>a</fr:tex> is positive. We fix semidirected <fr:tex>J \subseteq  A</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>a \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup {J} =  \bigsqcup { \mathopen {} \left ( { \mathopen {} \left \{ \bot \right \} \mathclose {}} \cup  J \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> to check that <fr:tex>J</fr:tex> is inhabited. We recall that <fr:tex>b \ll  a</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>a \sqsubseteq   \bigsqcup { \mathopen {} \left ( { \mathopen {} \left \{ \bot \right \} \mathclose {}} \cup  J \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, so it follows by the definition of the <fr:link
href="jms-002V.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-002V">way-below relation</fr:link> that either <fr:tex>b \sqsubseteq   \bot</fr:tex> or there exists <fr:tex>j \in  J</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>b \sqsubseteq  j</fr:tex>. The first case is contradictory by our assumption that <fr:tex>\lnot { \mathopen {} \left ( b= \bot \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, and the second case verifies that <fr:tex>J</fr:tex> is inhabited, so <fr:tex>a</fr:tex> is positive.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
